It was a girl, no more than five years old, with silver hair and indigo skin, wearing a frilly grey nightgown. She moved on silent feet and held a troll rag doll tight in one small hand. <br>
<br>
Though she had never met these people she knew who they were. Xosha, assassin and Hand of the Matron of the Shadows of the Blade and Xeylie, a young cleric who hoped to join the powerful guild. She did not know if they knew her, but she knew they would not be meeting her on this night. <br>
<br>
She regarded the sleeping women thoughtfully and grinned as she noticed the shiney rings on the rogue's relaxed hands. The child, still holding her toy, carefully slipped several of the prettiest jewelled rings off Xosha's slender hands and crept away again, silent as a mouse.... <br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/utyshalae.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tyshalae</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_purplespot.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10> at: 10/23/00 6:35:15 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/utyshalae.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tyshalae</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_purplespot.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Mouse</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#939393>(10/23/00 6:33:03 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.home.net/sbugelli/tyshface.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A Child's Afternoon in Neriak</span><hr size=1> Though she was not aware of it, Tyshalae W'Rath 's upbringing was considered something of an oddity by both the Noble and Common houses of Neriak. She, at the age of seven, still lived in her family's home, not in the guild house of the profession chosen for her by her elders. Nor was her upbringing left to anonymous caregivers, directed by cold and distant parents. <br>
<br>
Instead Tysh lived in a house full of affection and laughter, a rarity in any part of the Teir'dal city. She had a gentle, doting mother and a playful father. When they were away she was left in the care of the house Necromancer, who adored the child in his own strange way and acted as a surrogate grandfather to the child, teaching her as he had once taught her father. The child had even won the heart's of the House W'Rath's servants, who let her keep any treats her nimble little fingers managed to get a hold of. <br>
<br>
Nor was Tyshalae cloistered away in her home. She had been wandering the twisted streets of Neriak on her own for many moons, since she had first snuck out of the W'Rath compound. Tysh had followed Khevost, a favourite servant, out of the house and on his errands for her father and the necromancer, committing the layout of the city to memory. She and her troll rag-doll regularly wandered the streets, filching treats and shiny trinkets from the shopkeepers. Her parents had quickly discovered it was impossible to keep her from wandering and instead attempted to instill several important rules into her young mind. <br>
<br>
Tyshalae, unlike most Teir'dal her age, had little thought for her future role in life. She was only dimly aware of the fact that she was a Noble of the Respected Race and would be expected to follow a dignified path. None of her family's chosen roles held much interest for her. She did not have the stomach for gore that Momma and Papa Sol had, so Assassin and Necromancer were out of the question. She would never be muscular like Daddy with her thin frame, so his dream of a little Warrior would not be fulfilled with his first born. She had no love of the Gods thanks to her family's rather lax religious beliefs, so she would never hear the call of Innoruk like Momma's friend Yathrin. Tysh had no clue what the mad Talimar did, save that he always had candies hidden in the pockets of his brightly coloured robes for her. <br>
<br>
Her main goal for the future at this point in her young life was to see the forest. Tysh had heard stories of it, but had never managed to see it. She'd once made it all the way to the exit of the city and had seen the huge trees and strange mists when a guard picked her up by the back of her tunic and sent her home. <br>
<br>
The forest was her goal on this day, like many others. Tyshalae slowly snuck from shadow to shadow, hiding expertly at her tender age. As she made her way through the city she noticed that a particular Teir'dal was often in the same area as she was. He wore a robe like Talimar or Papa Sol, but looked similar to stern-faced General Zirrix, a friend of her parents whom she had just recently met when she tried to sneak into some boring meeting of Momma and Daddy's that was keeping them from home. <br>
<br>
She froze when she realized he was looking straight at her, though she knew she was well hidden. He walked towards her and spoke in a soft voice. &quot;Child, what do you know of the Magic Arts?&quot; <br>
<br>
Though she had ignored everything her parents had told her about not wandering off and not stealing, she remembered one important rule: Never talk to strangers. Tyshalae was running as fast as her long legs could go before the man had finished his sentence and did not slow until the gates of House W'Rath were in sight. <br>
<br>
When she entered the library, shaken but not afraid, the old Necromancer looked up at her with a slight smile on his face. &quot;Nice stroll child?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Ummm, yes Papa Sol.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Would you like me to read to you?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Yay,&quot; she squealed, climbing into the aged dark elf's lap. <br>
<br>
As she happily listened to the grim children's stories of the Teir'dal, her encounter with the strange man was quickly forgotten, though some small part of her childish mind knew this would not be the last that she saw of him. <br>
<br>
