<br>
In front of one great house a solitary child played. Tyshalae and her Quashie doll sat on the curb outside House W'Rath. The girl was chattering happily and perforating a recently decreased rat with a shinny dagger. Tysh had been eight years old for just over a day. When she had wakened the day before she had experienced the usual disappointment of not feeling any different on her birthday, but quickly got over it. Her Daddy and uncle Mourn would be returning home and she would get presents and sweets. <br>
<br>
Her Momma had originally been planning a great party of nobles for that evening, but had changed her mind rather quickly. It seemed that every time there was a noble gathering in recent months the host was robbed rather efficiently right afterwards. Tysh did not bother mentioning that she was the one doing the robbing, for she had no desire to spend her birthday in a itchy little dress listening to boring old nobles. Instead Morrigu planned a luncheon for family and friends. <br>
<br>
Tysh had gorged on all her favourite savouries and sweets, then got presents. Armour and daggers and lockpicks, rings and skulls and toys. The best gift was from her Daddy. Tysh had her heart set on a kitten, a cuddly little puff of fur. Her daddy carried a rather large wooden box over to her, grinning. Tysh had found her kitten inside, one almost of big as she was. <br>
<br>
&quot;It's a Sabertooth from the Overthere,&quot; he explained smiling. <br>
<br>
&quot;Sweet Innoruuk,&quot; Momma gasped. &quot;This creature's going to be the bane of our lives,&quot; thus christening the kitten. <br>
<br>
The giggling Necromancer, Oifur Moy'fur, the cast a spell on child, kitten and rag-doll, letting them fly through the house.... It had been the best birthday ever in Tysh's opinion. <br>
<br>
Now Tysh was testing out her new weapons and armour. Bane the kitten had to stay inside, for Momma was afraid he might try to eat one of the neighbourhood children. Tysh saw this as no great loss, but behaved for once. <br>
<br>
Tysh giggled as she poked the rat, spilling its innards in to the gutter. Quashie grinned appreciatively beside her. She then gasped as she felt staring eyes on her. A Teir'dal man was walking up the street towards her, a strange grin on his lips. <br>
<br>
&quot;Greetings child.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Ummmm, hello,&quot; Tysh mumbled, hiding her dagger beside her and stuffing Quashie into his special belt pouch. <br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;You are the W'Rath child, aren't you?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Ummmm.&quot; Tysh knew she wasn't to talk to strangers and stayed silent. <br>
<br>
&quot;You are. There are many in Neriak who want to teach you the right path child, to free you from the corruptness of your family. There are others who just want to play,&quot; he said, leering at her skinny young form. <br>
<br>
&quot;Don't you touch me,&quot; Tyshalae hissed. <br>
<br>
&quot;Come child, you like to play.&quot; He reached for her delicate shoulder. <br>
<br>
Tysh reacted quickly, remembering all her lessons from Momma and Daddy. She gashed the man's hand with the tip of her dagger then quickly dodged behind him. She drove her dagger into the back of his knee. The man fell with a moan and a curse. Tysh then kicked him in the groin and face with her pointy boots several times and stomped on his throat for good measure. <br>
<br>
Tysh knelt by the man's unmoving form and tugged on her dagger. It was stuck, caught on some bone or something. She frowned and looked up at the house. &quot;You stay here bad man,&quot; she hissed. <br>
<br>
Tysh stepped into the house and contemplated who to get. Momma and Daddy were having what Papa Sol called &quot;grown up time&quot; and were not to be bothered. Uncle Mourn would still be sleeping. She knew Papa Sol would be able to get her dagger back and wandered down the stairs to his study. <br>
<br>
&quot;What is it little one?&quot; he asked softly, looking up from an old book. <br>
<br>
&quot;My dagger....&quot; <br>
<br>
He frowned. &quot;Lost already?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;No, stuck.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Where child?&quot; <br>
<br>
Tysh grabbed his hand. &quot;Come with me Papa Sol,&quot; she said and led him outside. She pointed at the man. &quot;In his knee Papa Sol.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;What did he do to you?&quot; the old Necromancer whispered, staring at the limp figure's disfigured face. <br>
<br>
&quot;He tried to touch me,&quot; she mumbled. &quot;I think he wanted to do bad things to me&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;I see,&quot; he whispered, stroking the child's soft silvery hair. He knelt by the man and felt a faint pulse. Sol then pulled her dagger out of the man's knee and cleaned it on his robe. &quot;Here you go, my little one. You go inside and play with Quashie and Bane. I will clean this up.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Okies Papa Sol,&quot; Tysh said, hugging the Necromancer for just a second. She ran inside and found her kitten. Tysh, the kitten and Quashie then invented fun new games with lots for giggling, purring and clawing. By the time strange gurgling noises started echoing through the house from Papa Sol's lab in the basement, Tysh had forgotten her earlier fear. She barely noticed the noises or that they abruptly stopped. <br>
<br>
&quot;C'mon Quashie,&quot; Tysh said merrily, dangling her rag-doll by one little green arm. &quot;Let's find out if kittens like candy!&quot; Child, doll and kitten ran for the kitchen, trailing destruction in their wake. <br>
<br>
All was well within House W'Rath. <br>
